#’ Decompose a time series into its components: #’ - trend #’ - seasonality #’ - randomness

bike.dec <- decompose(bike.ts)
plot(bike.dec)

# Plot each component individually
plot(bike.dec$x, main = "Observed data")

  # ...the same as: plot(bike, type = "l")
plot(bike.dec$trend, main = "Trend")

plot(bike.dec$seasonal, main = "Seasonal")

plot(bike.dec$random, main = "Random")

# Set ARIMA parameters ----------------------------------------------------

#' Find value for I(d) parameter -------------------------------------------
#' d: How many non-seasonal differences are needed to 
#'    achieve stationarity (I)

#' We can use function ?diff() to compute differences between consecutive
#' elements of a series
diff(bike_weekly)
##            m.c.seq.row..seq.n...seq.col..drop...FALSE.
## 2011-01-02                                          NA
## 2011-01-09                                        7622
## 2011-01-16                                        -383
## 2011-01-23                                        -255
## 2011-01-30                                       -1071
## 2011-02-06                                        2574
## 2011-02-13                                         919
## 2011-02-20                                        3500

## 2012-12-31                                       -7991
# Plot Sales difference
plot(x = bike_weekly[-1],
     y = diff(bike_weekly), # lag = 1
     type = "l",
     xlab = "Weekly",
     ylab = "Sales",
     main = "Difference in Sales (lag=1)")

#' Visual analysis suggest that lag=1 results in stationary time series.
#' There is no need to look further differences.
#' We can consider the order of d to be 1.
d <- 1
# Find value for MA(q) parameter --------------------------------------------
#' q: Number of lagged forecast errors in the prediction equation (MA)

# Auto-correlation plot
forecast::Acf(bike_weekly)

{
  plotrix::draw.ellipse(x = 6.5, y = 0.57, a = 6.0, b = 0.15, angle = -3,
                        lty = 3, lwd = 2, border = "chocolate")
  text(x = 5.4, y = 0.64, "q = 12", col = "chocolate")
}

#' We can consider the order of q to be 5
q <- 5
# Find value for AR(p) parameter --------------------------------------------
#' p: Number of auto-regressive terms (AR)

# Partial auto-correlation plot
forecast::Acf(bike_weekly, type = "partial")

#' The partial autocorrelation function plot can be used to draw
#' a correlation between the time series and its lag. 
#' This plot lets us know about the lags that are not required
#' in the auto-regression part.
#' 
#' It can be noted that the first 1 lags are beyond the significance
#' limit.
{
  plotrix::draw.ellipse(x = 1.5, y = 0.80, a = 1, b = 0.10, angle = -2,
                        lty = 3, lwd = 3, border = "forestgreen")
  text(x = 3.1, y = 0.8, "p = 1", col = "forestgreen")
}

#' We can consider the order of p to be 2
p <- 2

#:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::: # Fit model - manually —————————————————- #::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

#' We'll fit the model with the function Arima() from the package 'forecast'

# Fit the ARIMA model with previously determined parameters
fit.arima <- arima(bike.ts,
                   order = c(p, d, q))
summary(fit.arima)
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = bike.ts, order = c(p, d, q))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ma1     ma2      ma3     ma4      ma5
##       0.5068  -0.8270  -0.7365  1.0746  -0.1232  0.0250  -0.0186
## s.e.  0.1175   0.0916   0.1551  0.1623   0.1598  0.1473   0.1172
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 21565859:  log likelihood = -1037.49,  aic = 2090.99
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                     ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set -2.716311 4621.948 3267.873 -4.233957 16.14259 0.9323308
##                    ACF1
## Training set 0.01045958
# Check residuals
# The 'residuals' in a time series model are what is left over after
# fitting the model. In a good model:
# - The residuals should be uncorrelated. If there are correlations
#   between residuals, then there is information left out of the model.
# - The residuals have zero mean. If the residuals have a mean other
#   than zero, then the forecasts are biased.
checkresiduals (fit.arima)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(2,1,5)
## Q* = 7.597, df = 13, p-value = 0.8688
## 
## Model df: 7.   Total lags used: 20
# Forecast sales
#' We can forecast the next values in the time series with function 'forecast'
# ?forecast::forecast.Arima
predict.arima <- forecast(fit.arima,
                          h = 6,            # number of periods for forecasting
                          level = c(80, 95) # confidence levels associated with the prediction intervals
                          )
plot(predict.arima,
     sub = "manual setting of parameters",
     col = "steelblue4",
     lwd = 2)

#::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
# Fit model - automatically -----------------------------------------------
#::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

# Auto-fit model with auto.arima()
# ?forecast::auto.arima()
fit.arima.auto <- auto.arima(bike_weekly,
                             allowdrift = FALSE,
                             ic = "aic")
summary(fit.arima.auto)
## Series: bike_weekly 
## ARIMA(0,2,2) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1     ma2
##       -1.2444  0.3427
## s.e.   0.1113  0.1100

## sigma^2 = 23306990:  log likelihood = -1029.81
## AIC=2065.61   AICc=2065.85   BIC=2073.54
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                     ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE      ACF1
## Training set -632.8725 4735.766 3302.336 -8.238292 16.74291 0.9421633 0.0135621
# Check residuals
checkresiduals(fit.arima.auto)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,2,2)
## Q* = 4.7475, df = 8, p-value = 0.7842
## 
## Model df: 2.   Total lags used: 10
# Forecast sales
predict.arima.auto <- forecast(fit.arima.auto, h = 6)
plot(predict.arima.auto,
     sub = "auto ARIMA",
     col = "navyblue",
     lwd = 2)

#' The best model can be chosen based on the lowest values of AIC or BIC.
#'   AIC: Akaike Information Criterion (Akaike, 1973)
#'   BIC: Bayesian Information Criterion (Schwarz, 1978)
#'   AICc: AIC corrected for small sample sizes (Hurvich and Tsai, 1989)
#'   
#' Statistical methods that can be seen as estimators of the prediction
#' error, therefore being helpful to evaluate and compare the performance
#' of different models. These methods penalize the use of large number of
#' predictive factors.
#' 
data.frame(AIC = round(c(fit.arima$aic, fit.arima.auto$aic), 1),
           AICc = round(c(fit.arima$aicc, fit.arima.auto$aic), 1),
           BIC = round(c(fit.arima$bic, fit.arima.auto$bic), 1),
           row.names = c("ARIMA", "auto.ARIMA"))
##               AIC   AICc    BIC
## ARIMA      2091.0 2065.6 2073.5
## auto.ARIMA 2065.6 2065.6 2073.5
